Georges Ohnet</link></novelist>
</writer>
</causal_agent>
</person>
</communicator>
</physical_entity>
.</p>
<p>

Millarde directed his last film in 1927 and died of a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../969/60969.xml">
heart attack</link> in <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../042/645042.xml">
New York City</link></village>
 in 1931 ten days shy of his forty-sixth birthday. He was married to actress <physical_entity wordnetid="100001930" confidence="0.8">
<person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.8">
<performer wordnetid="110415638" confidence="0.8">
<causal_agent wordnetid="100007347" confidence="0.8">
<actor wordnetid="109765278" confidence="0.8">
<entertainer wordnetid="109616922" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../857/2684857.xml">
June Caprice</link></entertainer>
</actor>
</causal_agent>
</performer>
</person>
</physical_entity>
 (1895-1936) whom he had directed in eight films for Fox. Ironically, she also died ten days before her birthday, succumbing to <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../219/105219.xml">
cancer</link> at the age of forty.</p>
<p>

Their daughter, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../195/3857195.xml">
June Elizabeth Millarde</link>, was thirteen years old when her mother died. Raised by her grandparents in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../315/18315.xml">
Long Island, New York</link>, she became a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../503/4324503.xml">
cover girl</link> known as "Toni Seven." The June 17, 1949 issue of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../600/31600.xml">
Time magazine</link> reported she was the heiress to an estimated $3,000,000 fortune.</p>

